<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-470-060  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 470 060.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Language  June 1990 v7 n6 p135(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Miller Freeman Publications 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The breakfast food cooker. (EOF)(humorous tale shows behavior ofcomputer scientists) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jones, Do-While.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>The breakfast food cooker Once upon a time, in a kingdom not far from here, aking summoned two of his advisors for a test.andP;  He showed them both a shinymetal box with two slots in the top, a control knob, and a lever.andP;  &quot;What doyou think this is?&quot;andM;One advisor, an engineer, answered first.andP;  &quot;It is a toaster,&quot; he said.andP;  Theking asked, &quot;How would you design an embedded computer for it?&quot;andP;  The engineerreplied, &quot;Using a four-bit microcontroller, I would write a simple programthat reads the darkness knob and quantizes its position to one of 16 shadesof darkness, from snow white to coal black.andP;  The program would use thatdarkness level as the index to a 16-element table of initial timer values.andO;Then it would turn on the heating elements and start the timer with theinitial value selected from the table.andP;  At the end of the time delay, itwould turn off the heat and pop up the toast.andP;  Come back next week, and I'llshow you a working prototype.&quot;andM;The second advisor, a computer scientist, immediately recognized the dangerof such short-sighted thinking.andP;  He said, &quot;Toasters don't just turn breadinto toast, they are also used to warm frozen waffles.andP;  What you see beforeyou is really a breakfast food cooker.andP;  As the subjects of your kingdombecome more sophisticated, they will demand more capabilities.andP;  They willneed a breakfast food cooker that can also cook sausage, fry bacon, and makescrambled eggs.andP;  A toaster that only makes toast will soon be obsolete.andP;  Ifwe don't look to the future, we will have to completely redesign the toasterin just a few years.andM;&quot;With this in  mind, we can formulate a more intelligent solution to theproblem.andP;  First, create a class of breakfast foods.andP;  Specialize this classinto subclasses: grains, pork, and poultry.andP;  The specialization processshould be repeated with grains divided into toast, muffins, pancakes, andwaffles; pork divided into sausage, links, and bacon; and poultry dividedinto scrambled eggs, hard-boiled eggs, poached eggs, fried eggs, and variousomelet classes.andM;&quot;The ham and cheese omelet class is worth special attention because it mustinherit characteristics from the pork, dairy, and poultry classes.andP;  Thus, wesee that the problem cannot be properly solved without multiple inheritance.andM;&quot;At run time, th program must create the proper object and send a message tothe object that says, 'Cook yourself.'andP;  The semantics of this message depend,of course, on the kind of object, so they have a different meaning to a pieceof toast than to scrambled eggs.andM;&quot;Reviewing the process so far, we see that the analysis phase has revealedthat the primary requirement is to cook any kind of breakfast food.andP;  In thedesign phase, we have discovered some derived requirements.andP;  Specifically, weneed an object-oriented language with multiple inheritance.andP;  Of course, usersdon't want the eggs to get cold while the bacon is frying, so concurrentprocessing is required, too.andM;&quot;We must not forget the user interface.andP;  The lever that lowers the food lacksversatility, and the darkness knob is confusing.andP;  Users won't buy the productunless it has a user-friendly, graphical interface.andP;  When the breakfastcooker is plugged in, users should see a cowboy boot on the screen.andP;  Usersclick on it, and the message 'Booting UNIX v. 8.3' appears on the screen.andO;(UNIX 8.3 should be out by the time the product gets to the market.)andP;  Userscan pull down a menu and click on the foods they want to cook.andM;&quot;Having made the wise decision of specifying the software first in the designphase, all that remains is to pick an adequate hardware platform for theimplementation phase.andP;  An Intel 80386 with 8MB of memory, a 30MB hard disk,and a VGA monitor should be sufficient.andP;  If you select a multitasking,object-oriented language that supports multiple inheritance and has abuilt-in GUI, writing the program will be a snap.andP;  (Imagine the difficulty wewould have had if we had foolishly allowed a hardware-first design strategyto lock us into a four-bit microcontroller!)&quot;andM;The king had the computer scientist thrown in the moat, and they all livedhappily ever after.andM;Do-While Jones plans large software projects for the defense industry andwrites the Ada Info column for the Journal of Pascal, Ada, and Modula-2.andP;  Hehas a B.S.andP;  in electrical engineering and has been granted a patent for aradar signal-processing algorithm.andO;</TEXT></DOC>